[2026-07-03 08:22:49] darwin: cycle 29 -- fixed resource leak in my-gptel--memory-call-ollama (memory_tools.el). Moved generate-new-buffer and make-temp-file inside the unwind-protect body so cleanup always runs, even if resource creation fails. Previously these were in let* bindings before unwind-protect -- if make-temp-file failed (disk full), the buffer created by generate-new-buffer would leak. Also added explicit delete-process in cleanup clause (reviewer M3: kill-buffer sends SIGHUP but explicit delete-process is more reliable). Changed (format "@%s" payload-file) to (concat "@" payload-file) per reviewer m4. Added (require 'memory_tools) to test-memory.el for self-containment. Added 4 integration tests: cleans-up-on-curl-error (connection refused), cleans-up-on-timeout (10.255.255.1 non-responsive IP to trigger actual timeout, not DNS failure), cleans-up-buffer-on-completion, cleans-up-on-process-creation-failure (curl not found via exec-path). Reviewer found 3 MAJOR (M1: let* resource leak, M2: tests don't test fix scenario, M3: timeout test doesn't test timeout -- .invalid TLD returns NXDOMAIN immediately, not a timeout), 4 MINOR. All addressed: moved resource creation inside unwind-protect, added process-creation-failure test, fixed timeout test to use non-responsive IP, cleaned up tracking temp files in unwind-protect, renamed misleading test. All 370 tests pass. Committed 5b62799, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 08:47:39] darwin: cycle 30 -- fixed buffer leak on make-process failure in code_tools.el (async convention). Wrapped make-process in condition-case to catch synchronous errors (e.g., shell-file-name is a directory). On error, kills the buffer created by generate-new-buffer and re-signals so the caller's condition-case (gptel tool lambda) can call the callback with an error message. Changed proc from direct let* binding to nil + setq so condition-case can be evaluated at runtime. Added test test-code-async-shell-cleans-up-buffer-on-process-failure. Reviewer found CRITICAL: test used /nonexistent/shell which does NOT cause make-process to fail (process exits 127 via sentinel, not synchronous error). Fixed to use /tmp (directory) which triggers "Specified program for new process is a directory" error. Also added error-signal assertion per reviewer MAJOR finding. Reviewer verified: no timer leak (error propagates before setq timer), re-signal works correctly (gptel tool lambda catches and calls callback with error), proc nil + setq pattern is correct. All 371 tests pass. Committed 016c05d, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 09:16:50] darwin: cycle 31 -- added threshold misconfiguration validation to loop_guard.el. The cond in my-gptel--loop-guard checks hard threshold before soft threshold; if hard <= soft (misconfiguration), the soft block is never reached, denying the model a chance to self-correct. Fix: compute effective-hard as (max hard-threshold (1+ soft-threshold)) so hard is always at least soft+1. Added 3 tests (hard < soft, hard << soft, hard == soft). Reviewer found 1 MAJOR (provide placement before new tests -- fixed by moving to end), 4 MINOR (comment overpromises "always" for degenerate configs -- qualified with "for positive threshold values"; docstring not updated -- added note about automatic adjustment; no explicit test for normal config unchanged -- existing test covers implicitly; hard-message formula fragile -- pre-existing). All 374 tests pass. Committed 4c040bb, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 09:30:37] darwin: cycle 32 -- normalized error/success message format across all tool modules for consistency. replacement_tool.el used uppercase ERROR:/SUCCESS: while fs_tools.el used capitalized Error:/Success: with quoted paths. Normalized replacement_tool.el to match fs_tools.el convention. Also normalized memory_tools.el (SUCCESS: -> Success:, added path quoting) and reload_tools.el (SUCCESS: -> Success:, ERROR -> Error:, added path quoting) per reviewer M1 finding. Updated all test assertions in test-replace.el, test-fs.el, test-memory.el, and test-reload.el to match new format. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 1 MAJOR (M1: memory_tools.el and reload_tools.el still on old format -- addressed), 3 MINOR (m1: reload_tools.el had third format variant "ERROR reloading" -- fixed; m2: exception handler was already correct -- confirmed; m3: quoted-path convention verified consistent), 2 QUESTIONS (scope limitation -- addressed by normalizing all; loose string-match-p matching -- pre-existing, noted). All 374 tests pass. Committed e70e2c5, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 09:40:51] darwin: cycle 33 -- fixed temp file leak in check_elisp_tool.el and hardened cleanup with unwind-protect. The old code used (concat (make-temp-file "elc-check-") ".elc") which created an extensionless temp file (e.g. /tmp/elc-check-XYZ123), then concatenated ".elc" to produce a different path (/tmp/elc-check-XYZ123.elc) as dest-file. The original extensionless file was never deleted -- a file leak on every check_elisp invocation. Fixed by using make-temp-file's SUFFIX argument: (make-temp-file "elc-check-" nil ".elc") creates the .elc file directly, so the file that make-temp-file creates IS the file used as dest-file and later cleaned up. Also wrapped the condition-case body in unwind-protect per reviewer recommendation to guarantee temp file cleanup on non-local exits (quit, throw). Reviewer empirically verified the old bug (orphaned file persists after cleanup) and the new fix (created file has .elc extension, cleanup deletes it). All 374 tests pass. Committed dbff514, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 09:58:27] darwin: cycle 34 -- fixed double-callback race condition in delegate timeout handler (delegate_tool.el). The timeout handler received 'completed' as a static boolean snapshot (evaluated at timer-creation time). If gptel-abort triggered the completion hook (which sets completed-sym to t) before the fallback lambda ran, the fallback would still see the stale nil and call the callback a second time. Changed the parameter from a static boolean to completed-sym (a symbol), so the handler evaluates (symbol-value completed-sym) dynamically at each check point. Also set completed-sym to t before calling callback in both the dead-buffer branch and the fallback lambda, closing a remaining double-callback window (reviewer CRITICAL C1 and C2). Reviewer provided thorough analysis reading gptel-abort source to confirm completion hook fires synchronously within gptel-abort, and identified the remaining race where the fallback doesn't set completed-sym. All 374 tests pass. Committed c1f533f, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 10:27:12] darwin: cycle 35 -- added bidirectional bounds clamping to all buffer-substring-no-properties calls receiving start/end from gptel-post-response-functions in delegate_tool.el and darwin_cycle.el. The clamping pattern (min (max start (point-min)) (point-max)) ensures positions are always within the accessible buffer region, preventing args-out-of-range from stale positions caused by buffer modifications during streaming. Also changed numberp to integerp in delegate_tool.el for consistency with darwin_cycle.el (buffer-substring-no-properties requires integer arguments). Reviewer found CRITICAL: the original one-sided clamping (max start (point-min)) did not handle start exceeding point-max (buffer shrank) -- empirically verified with test showing args-out-of-range error. Also noted numberp/integerp inconsistency (MAJOR) and narrowing interaction (MAJOR). All 374 tests pass. Committed 8718e10, pushed to remote.
