[2026-07-03 11:14:54] darwin: cycle 37 -- added path traversal validation to my-gptel--get-agent-dir (task_tools.el). The function resolves the current agent's directory from buffer-local variables (my-gptel--current-agent-name or my-gptel--current-agent-file), both declared safe-local-variable for stringp in session_persistence.el. A tampered session file could set the name to ../../etc/passwd, causing path traversal. Added regex validation (^[a-zA-Z0-9_-]+$) matching the pattern already used in my-gptel--load-agent-profile (delegate_tool.el) and my-gptel-tool-read-history (task_tools.el). Also added file-truename containment check (string-prefix-p agent-dir (file-truename resolved)) per reviewer M1, matching the defense-in-depth pattern in delegate_tool.el -- the regex blocks direct traversal characters but not symlink-based escapes. Reviewer found 1 CRITICAL (missing test for traversal through agent-file fallback -- added), 4 MAJOR (no truename containment -- added; safe-local-variable too permissive -- noted as follow-up; regex duplicated across 4 sites -- noted; session_persistence.el:109 unvalidated path construction -- pre-existing, noted), 3 MINOR (error message includes user input, missing empty-string test -- added, fixture doesn't save/restore agent-file). Added 9 tests: valid name, no agent, path traversal, slashes, dots, spaces, fallback to agent-file, fallback with traversal file, empty string rejection. All 385 tests pass. Committed 26f2bdc, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 12:37:53] darwin: cycle 38 -- added session name validation to prevent path traversal in session saving (session_persistence.el). New function my-gptel--validate-session-name validates session names using string-anchored regex (\`[a-zA-Z0-9._-]+\') before use in expand-file-name. Uses string anchors (not line anchors) to prevent multi-line bypass where ^...$ matches at each newline boundary. my-gptel-save-session now wraps the session name through validation before constructing the file path. This closes a path traversal vector noted by reviewer in cycle 37: the session name (from user input or programmatic callers) was directly interpolated into expand-file-name without validation. Added 7 tests: valid names, path traversal rejection, empty/nil rejection, spaces rejection, special chars rejection (with :type user-error), and integration test. Reviewer found 2 MAJOR (default-name UX with malicious agent name -- not a security issue, validation catches it; no symlink containment -- pre-existing, noted), 5 MINOR (inconsistent :type in special chars test -- fixed; regex consistency with task_tools.el line anchors -- noted as follow-up; no null-byte test -- noted). All 393 tests pass. Committed 31b97dc, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 12:45:27] darwin: cycle 39 -- DRY refactoring: extracted duplicated agent name validation regex from 4 call sites into shared functions in task_tools.el. New my-gptel--valid-agent-name-p (predicate) and my-gptel--validate-agent-name (validator) use string anchors (\`...\') instead of line anchors (^...$) to prevent multi-line bypass. Updated directory-files regex at line 139 from ^...$ to \`...\' for consistency. Improved error message to include allowed characters. Added defense-in-depth comment in reload_tools.el. session_persistence.el intentionally NOT unified (allows dots for session names). delegate_tool.el and reload_tools.el now (require 'task_tools). Reviewer found 1 CRITICAL (directory-files regex still used line anchors -- fixed), 1 MAJOR (double validation in reload_tools.el -- documented as defense-in-depth), 3 MINOR (load-order dependency, error vs user-error, error message -- improved message). All 391 tests pass. Committed 114e253, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 13:17:12] darwin: cycle 40 -- replaced all remaining regex line anchors ($ and ^) with string anchors (\\' and \\`) across init.d/ and test/ files. Changed 14 $ -> \\' patterns and 1 ^...$ -> \\`...\\' pattern in 7 files: file_guard.el (7 security-critical path matching patterns), agent_loader.el (1 directory-files regex), session_persistence.el (2 directory-files regexes), output_sanitizer.el (2 injection marker end anchors), test-fs.el (3 patterns), test-replace.el (1 pattern), test-gptel.el (1 pattern). Line anchors match at each newline boundary; string anchors match only at actual string boundaries. This is a security improvement: a path like /init.el\\n../../etc would match /init\\.el$ but correctly fails with /init\\.el\\'. Consistent with cycles 38-39 pattern. The ^ in output_sanitizer.el injection markers intentionally kept (sanitizer processes line-by-line via split-string, so ^ matches start of each individual line string). The ^ in session_persistence.el re-search-forward also kept (buffer search where ^ means beginning-of-line). Reviewer found 1 MINOR (M1: two ^ in test-fs.el error assertions not migrated -- addressed by changing to \\`). Reviewer also noted Q1 (auto-mode-alist already used \\' -- pre-existing correct usage) and Q2 (agent name regex intentionally doesn't allow dots unlike session name regex). All 391 tests pass. Committed 311176d, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 13:41:16] darwin: cycle 41 -- added 11 tests for darwin--notify-telegram and darwin--notify-on-exit (darwin_cycle.el, 7% coverage). Tests cover: skip paths (3, with call-process mock verifying NOT called), payload construction (JSON structure verified via json-read), success detection, failure detection, empty response handling, special character round-trip (exact equal), notify-on-exit with/without message, and hook registration. Reviewer found 2 CRITICAL: (1) mock used (bufferp buffer) but production code passes t (not a buffer object) as DESTINATION to call-process -- (bufferp t) is nil, so the mock never inserted responses, making success/failure/empty tests all exercise the same empty-response path. Fixed by checking (or (bufferp destination) (eq destination t)) and inserting into current buffer when destination is t. (2) All success/failure/skip tests used vacuous (should t) assertions -- always pass regardless of code path. Fixed by mocking 'message to capture log output and asserting on 'sent successfully' vs 'FAILED' vs 'skipped'. Skip tests now mock call-process and assert it was never called. Also fixed fragile URL assertion (positional indexing -> cl-some search) and strengthened special chars test (substring match -> exact equal). All 402 tests pass. Committed ac7fe46, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 13:57:42] darwin: cycle 42 -- fixed temp file leak in my-gptel--memory-write-memories (memory_tools.el). The old code created a temp file with make-temp-file, wrote content via with-temp-file, then renamed. If rename-file failed (e.g., target directory doesn't exist), the temp file was orphaned. Fixed by wrapping write+rename in unwind-protect with condition-case, cleaning up the temp file on any error. Moved make-temp-file inside condition-case so its failure returns an Error: string instead of signaling (honoring the function's return contract). Added ignore-errors on cleanup delete-file for defensive best-effort reclamation. Also fixed the caller my-gptel-summarize-memories: it unconditionally called my-gptel-tool-reload-agent and reported success even when the write failed, producing contradictory messages like "Error: Failed to write... 5 entries written." Now branches on the write result. Added test test-memory-write-cleans-up-temp-on-rename-failure using cl-set-difference for concurrency-safe temp file verification. Reviewer found 2 MAJOR (make-temp-file outside condition-case -- fixed; test count-based assertion fragile -- fixed with set-difference), 3 MINOR (delete-file could signal -- wrapped in ignore-errors; dead code in test -- removed; misleading variable name -- renamed), 2 QUESTIONS (NFS atomicity -- noted; caller doesn't check write result -- fixed). All 403 tests pass. Committed 9e0ad0f, pushed to remote.
