[2026-07-03 14:45:17] darwin: cycle 44 -- fixed derived-mode-p misuse for gptel-mode minor mode check in agent_loader.el. gptel-mode is a minor mode (define-minor-mode), but derived-mode-p checks the major mode hierarchy. (derived-mode-p 'gptel-mode) always returned nil, so the guard (when (not (derived-mode-p 'gptel-mode)) ...) always evaluated to true, meaning gptel-mode 1 was always called even when already active. Benign in practice (calling a minor mode with 1 when already on is a no-op), but semantically wrong. Replaced with (unless (bound-and-true-p gptel-mode) (gptel-mode 1)), the correct check for minor mode active state. Updated test docstring to match. Reviewer approved with 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 1 MINOR (pre-existing test limitation: test-agent-load-agent-preserves-existing-gptel-mode would pass with old code too since gptel-mode 1 is a no-op when already active -- noted but not worth mocking for a one-line fix). All 410 tests pass. Committed 692c236, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 14:58:44] darwin: cycle 45 -- fixed infinite loop in darwin-run-cycle batch-mode event loop for stuck non-terminal FSM. The cond form in the event loop had three branches (terminal+not-pending -> exit, terminal+pending -> incf, no-fsm+idle>60 -> exit) but no else branch. If the FSM was in a non-terminal state (WAIT, TOOL, etc.) with no active requests, none of the three branches matched. The cond fell through without incrementing idle-count, so the 1800s safety net never triggered -- the while loop spun forever. Added a t (else) branch that increments idle-count for any unhandled case. Also covers the case where fsm is nil and idle-count <= 60 (lets it build up to trigger branch 3's faster 60s exit). Reviewer approved with 0 CRITICAL, 3 MAJOR (all pre-existing: no-FSM comment coverage, delegate-active safety gap, no test coverage for event loop), 3 MINOR (comment could mention no-FSM case -- fixed, branch ordering redundancy -- noted, gptel-fsm-p vs cl-typep -- confirmed correct). Updated comment per reviewer M1 to mention the no-FSM case. All 410 tests pass. Committed 2104088, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 15:21:29] darwin: cycle 46 -- added missing (require 'gptel) to code_tools.el, fs_tools.el, and replacement_tool.el. These modules used gptel-tools via add-to-list and gptel-make-tool without explicitly requiring gptel. The check_elisp tool didn't catch these warnings because it runs in the full Emacs environment where gptel is already loaded. Warnings only appear during standalone byte-compilation without the full init.el load chain. Also added declare-function for my-gptel-tool-reload-agent in memory_tools.el (used declare-function instead of require to avoid potential circular dependency with reload_tools.el). Reviewer identified replacement_tool.el as having the same issue but not being fixed in the initial change -- fixed per reviewer feedback. The reviewer empirically verified that replacement_tool.el produces the same gptel-tools free variable and gptel-make-tool unknown function warnings when compiled without gptel available, confirming it was the same class of issue. All 410 tests pass. Committed 4e305cd, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 15:40:35] darwin: cycle 47 -- fixed race condition crash in my-gptel-list-sessions (session_persistence.el) and hardened my-gptel--sort-sessions-by-mtime against vanished files. The format call (format "%8d" (file-attribute-size attrs)) would crash with "Format specifier doesn't match argument type" if a session file was deleted between directory-files and file-attributes (TOCTOU race). Initial fix wrapped size with (or ... 0), but reviewer found 3 issues: (1) CRITICAL: test didn't exercise the fix because directory-files doesn't list deleted files; (2) MAJOR: format-time-string with nil mtime shows current time (misleading); (3) MAJOR: sort function has same nil-attrs vulnerability, and my-gptel-open-session (which also calls sort) was unpatched. Revised fix: centralized vanished-file filtering in my-gptel--sort-sessions-by-mtime itself -- files with nil attrs are now filtered out with a warning BEFORE sorting. This protects both callers (list-sessions and open-session) and eliminates the redundant file-attributes call in list-sessions. Simplified list-sessions mapcar (no longer needs its own delq nil). Updated nonexistent-file sort test to verify filtering instead of documenting old pass-through behavior. Added new test test-session-list-handles-vanished-file that mocks directory-files to include a ghost path, captures message output, and verifies ghost is excluded from output + warning logged. All 411 tests pass. Committed da8d455, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 16:07:23] darwin: cycle 48 -- added buf return value to my-gptel--spawn-async-delegate (delegate_tool.el) and 18 new tests (24 -> 42 total). The function created a buffer via get-buffer-create but never returned it -- callers couldn't access the delegate buffer. Added buf as last form in let* body. Also added tests for spawn-async-delegate (0% coverage): buffer creation, depth tracking (default + increment from parent), prompt insertion, system prompt, hook registration (completion, pre-tool, stream), delegate tool removal at max depth, tool preservation below max depth, gptel-confirm-tool-calls nil. Stream edge cases: dead parent buffer, nil stream-pos. Completion hook edge cases: nil start/end, start > end, non-integer start, timer cancellation (both case 1 and case 3). Reviewer found timer leaks in cancel-timer tests (real timers created but cancel-timer mocked) -- fixed by cancelling real timers after cl-letf scope. Also moved provide to end of file. All 429 tests pass. Committed 29dc304, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 16:44:17] darwin: cycle 49 -- scoped self-modification mode to darwin cycle buffer only (setq -> setq-local) in darwin_cycle.el. Previously, (setq my-gptel--guard-allow-self-modification t) set the GLOBAL value to t, meaning ALL buffers -- including delegate sub-agent buffers (e.g., reviewer) -- had self-modification enabled and could modify init.d/*.el files. With setq-local, only the *darwin-cycle* buffer has the buffer-local t binding; delegate buffers inherit the global nil value and cannot modify protected Emacs Lisp source files. This is a security improvement: it limits self-modification privilege to darwin only, preventing sub-agents from modifying tool code. Reviewer confirmed: gptel--handle-tool-use wraps tool calls in (with-current-buffer (plist-get info :buffer) ...), so guard checks run in the requesting buffer's context. Darwin's buffer sees t, delegate buffers see nil. No code paths require delegates to have self-modification. The global value remains nil, so future non-darwin sessions are also protected. Reviewer noted 2 MINOR: (1) execute_code_local bypasses file guard entirely (pre-existing, not introduced by this change), (2) no test covers buffer-local isolation behavior. All 429 tests pass. Committed 03dcd02, pushed to remote.
