[2026-07-03 17:12:06] darwin: cycle 51 -- tightened safe-local-variable predicates to prevent path traversal from tampered session files. Replaced bare #'stringp declarations for my-gptel--current-agent-name and my-gptel--current-agent-file with validating predicates (my-gptel--safe-agent-name-p and my-gptel--safe-agent-file-p) in session_persistence.el. The name predicate uses the same regex as my-gptel--valid-agent-name-p (string anchors, [a-zA-Z0-9_-]+). The file predicate checks: stringp, ends in "prompt.org", no ".." substring. Also updated stale docstring in task_tools.el that referenced old #'stringp. Added 5 tests covering valid/invalid names and file paths including multi-line bypass. Reviewer found 2 MAJOR (stale docstring -- fixed; overstrict .. check needs documentation -- added note to docstring), 5 MINOR (null byte gap -- noted; no agents.d path check -- noted as defense-in-depth; missing multi-line test for file predicate -- added; regex duplication with task_tools.el -- noted as intentional). All 433 tests pass. Committed fe6a2a3, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 17:24:31] darwin: cycle 52 -- fixed log injection vulnerability in audit_log.el. Added my-gptel--audit-sanitize-detail function that replaces newlines (\n) and carriage returns (\r) with their visible escaped representations (\\n, \\r) before writing to the audit log. Without this, a filepath or command containing newlines could inject fake audit log entries on new lines, making them indistinguishable from real entries. The detail field comes from user-controlled input (filepaths from tool calls, shell commands from execute_code_local). Modified my-gptel--audit-log to call the sanitizer on the detail argument. Added defense-in-depth comment in docstring documenting that tool and agent fields are not sanitized (trusted by invariant -- tool is always a hardcoded literal, agent is validated by my-gptel--safe-agent-name-p). Added 9 tests: newline/carriage-return/mixed sanitization, clean string pass-through, non-string input (prin1-to-string), empty string, only-newlines, and two integration tests verifying malicious filepaths and commands produce single-line log entries. Also added (require 'audit_log) to test-audit.el for self-containment and moved (provide 'test-audit) to end of file. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 1 MAJOR (document tool/agent trust invariant -- addressed with docstring comment), 6 MINOR (Unicode U+2028/U+2029 not sanitized -- low risk, don't create actual newlines in file; null byte not sanitized -- low risk for Emacs-based log reading; setq style -- kept for readability; pre-existing old-log-path warning -- pre-existing; test coverage gaps -- added empty string and only-newlines tests; truncation order question -- truncation before sanitization is correct). All 442 tests pass. Committed 7fdf1ab, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 17:40:20] darwin: cycle 53 -- fixed narrowing bug in my-gptel--memory-extract-conversation (memory_tools.el). The function used buffer-substring-no-properties from (point-min) to (point-max) without widening first. If the gptel buffer was narrowed (during streaming or by user action), point-min/point-max return the narrowed region boundaries, so the extracted conversation would be incomplete -- the summarizer would produce memories based on only a partial conversation. Fix: wrapped body in (save-restriction (widen) ...) to ensure full buffer content is always extracted, while restoring original narrowing afterward. Added 2 tests: widens-narrowed-buffer (verifies all text extracted from narrowed buffer AND narrowing restored after call) and truncates-when-narrowed (verifies truncation operates on full widened buffer, not just narrowed region). Also fixed obsolete point-at-bol -> line-beginning-position per reviewer m1, moved provide to end of file per reviewer m2. Reviewer found 2 MAJOR (M1: test doesn't verify narrowing restoration -- addressed by adding assertion that buffer is still narrowed after call; M2: no test for truncation+narrowing interaction -- addressed by adding truncates-when-narrowed test), 3 MINOR (obsolete function, provide placement, docstring ambiguity -- first two addressed). All 444 tests pass. Committed 936f251, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 18:00:50] darwin: cycle 54 -- expanded darwin--cycle-complete-p completion phrase regex. Added 'cycle is done' as a new literal alternation to handle natural language variations like "The cycle is done." Initial attempt also added `finished[^c]*cycle`, `cycle.*summary`, `summary.*cycle`, and `cycle.*done` but reviewer found critical issues: (1) `finished[^c]*cycle` was a regression -- `[^c]` matches newlines in Emacs regex (unlike `.`), making it broader not narrower, and fails on phrases like "finished the current cycle" where 'c' appears between the words; (2) `cycle.*done` matches "not done yet" text causing premature cycle termination; (3) `cycle.*summary` and `summary.*cycle` match planning text. Reverted all problematic patterns, kept only the safe literal `cycle is done`. Reviewer also identified pre-existing false positive risks in `all steps` (matches "haven't completed all steps yet") and `finished.*cycle` (matches "finished the review before the cycle started") -- noted for future cycles. Added 4 new tests: cycle-is-done positive, finished-current-cycle positive (verifies `.` handles 'c' between words), not-done-yet false positive, cycle-summary-without-HISTORY negative. All 448 tests pass. Committed 57c0d86, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 18:19:44] darwin: cycle 55 -- tightened 'all steps' completion regex in darwin--cycle-complete-p to prevent false positives and allow natural phrasing. Replaced overly broad 'all steps' alternation with 'all steps (are |have been )?done' and 'all steps (are |have been )?complete'. The old 'all steps' matched inside 'haven't completed all steps yet' (false positive causing premature cycle termination). The new alternations allow optional 'are ' or 'have been ' between 'steps' and 'done'/'complete' to match natural phrasing like 'all steps are done' and 'all steps have been done'. Reviewer empirically verified false positives ('Not all steps done' -> MATCH, should be NIL) and false negatives ('All steps are done' -> NIL, should be MATCH) with the initial tightening. Added optional words to fix false negatives. Documented 'Not all steps done' as a known limitation (Emacs regex lacks negative lookbehind; region-scoped search mitigates in practice). Also moved (provide 'darwin_cycle) from mid-file to end (fixing placement from cycle 54) and (provide 'test-darwin-cycle) to end of test file. Added 7 tests. All 455 tests pass. Committed b015d8e, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 19:12:08] darwin: cycle 56 -- added structured CYCLE_COMPLETE sentinel for cycle completion detection in darwin--cycle-complete-p (darwin_cycle.el). The sentinel is a line-anchored, case-sensitive literal string that the model outputs on its own line to unambiguously signal cycle completion. Checked first via short-circuit or, before the natural language patterns. Does not require HISTORY reference (structured signal, not natural language). Also updated darwin-cycle-prompt step 11 to instruct the model to end with CYCLE_COMPLETE on its own line. Reviewer found 2 CRITICAL issues: (1) prompt text itself contains "CYCLE_COMPLETE" as a substring in a sentence -- a plain substring match would false-positive on the prompt text in the buffer (especially via the nil start/end full-buffer fallback path); (2) string-match-p does substring matching, so CYCLE_COMPLETED, MY_CYCLE_COMPLETE, and cycle_complete (case-insensitive) would all match. Also found MAJOR issues: misleading test name (case-sensitive test actually tested case-insensitive), no test for substring false positive, no test for in-sentence false positive. All addressed: changed to line-anchored regex \\(^\\|\n\\)CYCLE_COMPLETE\\(\n\\|\\'\\) requiring the sentinel on its own line, made sentinel check case-sensitive (let case-fold-search nil for sentinel only, natural language patterns remain case-insensitive), added tests for substring rejection, in-sentence rejection, case sensitivity (lowercase rejected), and buffer start/end edge cases. All 464 tests pass. Committed bacbae7, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 19:29:59] darwin: cycle 57 -- added CYCLE_COMPLETE sentinel reminder to darwin-cycle-continue-prompt (darwin_cycle.el), fixed missing (provide 'code_tools) in code_tools.el, and added (require 'module) to 7 test files for self-containment (test-code, test-fs, test-file-guard, test-sanitizer, test-loop, test-task, test-check). The continue prompt now ends with "end with the exact text CYCLE_COMPLETE on its own line" so the model is reminded of the structured sentinel on every continuation, not just the initial prompt. code_tools.el had no provide form, meaning (require 'code_tools) would fail -- discovered when adding require to test-code.el. Reviewer found M1 (test-check.el missing require for check_elisp_tool -- fixed) and m2 (continue prompt wording should match initial prompt's "exact text" phrasing -- fixed). All 464 tests pass. Committed 0b66d67, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 19:55:10] darwin: cycle 58 -- fixed post-sort TOCTOU race in my-gptel-list-sessions display mapcar (session_persistence.el). The sort function already filters vanished files (cycle 47), but a second TOCTOU race existed: a file could vanish AFTER sort returns but BEFORE file-attributes is called in the display mapcar. If attrs is nil, file-attribute-size/file-attribute-modification-time on nil would crash with "Format specifier doesn't match argument type". Fix: wrapped display mapcar's file-attributes in nil check, skip with warning (matching sort function pattern), filter via delq nil. Added test test-session-list-handles-vanished-file-after-sort that mocks sort to pass through both files, then mocks file-attributes to return nil for ghost (simulating post-sort vanishing). Reviewer approved with minor cosmetic notes (mock mtime at wrong index, duplicated warning message, redundant cleanup, let* vs let). All 469 tests pass. Committed 3fc53f3, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-03 20:12:24] darwin: cycle 59 -- optimized append_file direct-to-disk path in fs_tools.el to read only the last byte instead of the entire file for trailing newline check. Uses insert-file-contents with START/END arguments (partial read). Also added nil-attrs guard for TOCTOU (file could vanish between file-attributes and insert-file-contents). Reviewer found CRITICAL: the inner insert-file-contents error was unhandled -- if file vanishes between file-attributes and insert-file-contents, the error propagated to the outer condition-case causing the entire append to fail. Fixed by wrapping insert-file-contents in its own condition-case defaulting to empty prefix, allowing write-region to create the file fresh. Reviewer also identified missing test cases: size=1 edge case (both with and without newline), large file WITH trailing newline, and true TOCTOU race. Added 7 tests total: large-file-partial-read (200KB no newline), vanished-file-no-crash (nil attrs), empty-file-zero-size, single-byte-no-newline (size=1), single-byte-with-newline (size=1), large-file-with-trailing-newline (200KB with newline), and toctou-vanished-between-attrs-and-read (mocked file-attributes to simulate file existing at attrs time but not at read time). All 476 tests pass. Committed 78084e3, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 05:37:28] darwin: cycle 60 -- fixed failing test test-unknown-tool-fsm-recovery. gptel was updated externally from 0.9.9.5 to 20260704.707 (elpa/ is gitignored). The new gptel version handles unknown tools gracefully: gptel--handle-tool-use now calls gptel--process-tool-call with an error message, which sets :result on the tool-call and transitions the FSM from TOOL through TRET to WAIT. The old test asserted the FSM stayed in TOOL state with no :result (documenting old gptel behavior where unknown tools were silently skipped). Updated test to assert new correct behavior: FSM transitions to WAIT, :result is set with error message containing "not available", callback is called with tool-result. Also updated file header comment and test docstring to reflect new gptel behavior. Reviewer provided thorough analysis tracing the full FSM transition chain (TOOL->TRET->WAIT) and identified that the condition-case catches errors from gptel--handle-wait which fires a real network request when FSM reaches WAIT -- this is a known side effect but not a test failure. All 476 tests pass. Committed 8704f96, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 05:55:15] darwin: cycle 61 -- fixed dead-buffer crash in async shell sentinel (code_tools.el). The sentinel lambda in my-gptel--async-shell-command accessed the process buffer via (with-current-buffer buf (buffer-string)) without checking buffer-live-p. If the buffer was killed between process exit and sentinel execution (re-entrancy window during accept-process-output in the legacy sync path, or double-sentinel invocation), with-current-buffer would signal "Selecting deleted buffer". Fixed by guarding with buffer-live-p and returning a diagnostic marker string "[buffer was no longer live — output lost]" when the buffer is dead, making the condition observable in logs rather than silently returning empty string. Reviewer approved with 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 2 suggestions (observable marker adopted, short-circuit sanitization noted as minor optimization). All 476 tests pass. Committed d51ea6d, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 06:14:08] darwin: cycle 62 -- fixed audit log exit code for timed-out commands (code_tools.el). The sentinel in my-gptel--async-shell-command called my-gptel--audit-log-exec with exit=0 when a command timed out, because delete-process causes process-exit-status to return nil (not a non-zero code), and the old condition (and exit-code (/= exit-code 0)) fell through to the else branch 0. This was misleading: a timeout is not a success. Fixed by checking timed-out first and passing -1 as the exit code. Updated docstring of my-gptel--audit-log-exec in audit_log.el to document -1 for timeouts. Added test test-audit-log-exec-timeout-exit-code. Reviewer found 2 MAJOR: (1) test was placed after (provide 'test-audit) -- fixed by moving before provide; (2) no integration test verifies the actual sentinel path -- noted as a gap but the unit test is sufficient for this change. Also noted pre-existing unused old-log-path warning in with-audit-fixture macro. All 477 tests pass. Committed d31a4ca, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 06:24:52] darwin: cycle 63 -- fixed dead-buffer crash in my-gptel--memory-call-ollama (memory_tools.el). The function called (with-current-buffer buf (buffer-string)) without checking buffer-live-p after the accept-process-output loop. If the buffer was killed during event processing (by a sentinel or filter), with-current-buffer would signal "Selecting deleted buffer". Fixed by wrapping buffer access in buffer-live-p check, returning empty string if dead. Also added a dedicated cond branch for the dead-buffer case (per reviewer M1) that produces a clear "Process buffer was killed during summarization" error instead of a misleading timeout message. Eliminated redundant second buffer-string call in the timeout branch by reusing raw-output (already captured before the cond). Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 3 MINOR (dead-buffer+timeout misleading error -- addressed with dedicated branch; delete-process sentinel comment -- strengthened; temp file permissions -- noted as fine). All 477 tests pass. Committed da39a30, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 06:40:51] darwin: cycle 64 -- fixed typo 'branitched' -> 'branched' in memory_tools.el comment (introduced in cycle 63). Consolidated redundant active-request detection in darwin_cycle.el batch-mode event loop: removed delegate-active loop (cl-some checking live buffer AND delegate name match OR get-buffer-process) that was a strict subset of the active-requests loop (dolist checking live buffer). The get-buffer-process check was effectively a no-op for curl-based requests since the curl process is on a temp buffer, not the chat buffer. Simplified to single cl-some with buffer-live-p. Updated stale comment referencing old delegate-name and get-buffer-process checks per reviewer M2. Reviewer confirmed simplification is logically equivalent: delegate-active was a subset of active-requests, so (or active-requests delegate-active) == active-requests. All 477 tests pass. Committed 5cfad34, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 07:01:19] darwin: cycle 65 -- added audit log rotation to prevent unbounded growth (audit_log.el). Added my-gptel--audit-log-max-size defcustom (default 10MB, nil to disable) and my-gptel--audit-maybe-rotate function. When the audit log exceeds max-size, it is renamed to audit.log.1 (overwriting any previous rotation) and a fresh log is started. Rotation is best-effort (condition-case nil) matching existing error-resilience pattern. Added guard for negative max-size values per reviewer m5. Removed redundant delete-file before rename-file per reviewer m2 (rename-file with t already overwrites). Documented single-generation retention limitation in defcustom docstring per reviewer M1. Added 5 tests: rotation triggers when exceeding max-size, no rotation under max-size, no rotation when nil, overwrite old .1 file, non-existent log handling. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 1 MAJOR (single-generation retention -- documented), 5 MINOR (redundant delete-file -- removed; old-log-path pre-existing warning; max-size not in fixture -- tests use let; negative max-size -- added guard; missing boundary test size==max-size -- noted). All 482 tests pass. Committed b4760df, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 07:16:17] darwin: cycle 66 -- suffixed directory entries with / in list_directory output (fs_tools.el). my-gptel--fs-list-directory now appends / to directory entries to distinguish them from files, helping the AI agent decide whether to list_directory into a path or read_file from it. The lambda wrapping the sort output checks file-directory-p for each entry and appends / if it's a directory. Updated docstring to mention the suffix convention. Added test test-fs-list-directory-suffixes-directories with exact line matching (split-string + member) per reviewer m1 feedback. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 4 MINOR (test substring matching -> fixed with exact line matching; per-entry stat syscall noted as acceptable; symlinks-to-dirs get / which is correct; broken symlinks get no / which is acceptable), 1 QUESTION (existing test still uses substring match for subdir -- noted as intentional since it still passes). All 483 tests pass. Committed 8183fad, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 07:43:46] darwin: cycle 67 -- fixed multi-line injection vulnerability in my-gptel--safe-agent-file-p (session_persistence.el). Added control character check rejecting newlines (\n), carriage returns (\r), and null bytes (\0) in agent file path values from tampered session files. Previously only \n was checked (added in cycle 51), leaving \r and \0 as injection vectors. A crafted session file could set my-gptel--current-agent-file to a value like "/etc/passwd\0/root/prompt.org" which ends in prompt.org and passes all other checks, but the null byte could cause C-level string truncation. Also fixed misleading test comment from cycle 51: the test value "/root/prompt.org\n/etc/passwd" does NOT end in prompt.org (ends in /etc/passwd), so it was rejected by the suffix check, not by newline handling. Added proper test cases for \n, \r, and \0 attack vectors that DO end in prompt.org. Initial attempt was to rewrite my-gptel--session-restore-custom-state to fix global state leakage, but reviewer found the premise was factually incorrect (find-file already creates buffer-local bindings for defvar variables via make-local-variable) and the change introduced a regression. Reverted and pivoted to the security fix identified by the reviewer's analysis of the test. Reviewer also suggested using an allowlist regex instead of blocklisting individual characters -- noted as future improvement. All 483 tests pass. Committed 140fb8c, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 08:19:26] darwin: cycle 68 -- three small fixes: (1) typo in output_sanitizer.el copyright header 'Randoso' -> 'Randazzo', (2) stale comment in check_elisp_tool.el referencing removed LOAD argument (byte-compile-file no longer accepts it in Emacs 30+, code was fixed in cycle 8 but comment was left stale), (3) rewrote my-gptel--delegate-continue-prompt in delegate_tool.el -- old prompt said 'You have not used any tools yet' which is factually incorrect when tools were used in previous turns (tools-called-sym is reset between turns), old prompt also forced tool usage even when task was complete; new prompt correctly says 'Your last response did not include any tool calls' and gives model explicit option to produce final response if task is complete. Also updated two stale docstrings (my-gptel--delegate-max-turns and my-gptel--delegate-completion-fn) per reviewer feedback to match corrected wording. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 2 MINOR (both stale docstrings -- fixed), 2 QUESTIONS (no test for prompt text, no multi-turn test -- noted as future). All 483 tests pass. Committed ddac6c5, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 08:37:01] darwin: cycle 69 -- strengthened smoke test loadability verification and added provide to 5 init.d modules. The old smoke-all-init-modules-loadable test only checked (file-exists-p) for each .el file -- vacuous, passes even if module fails to load. Added (provide 'module-name) to locale.el, ui_cleanup.el, package_setup.el, gptel_setup.el, evil_mode.el (5 modules that previously lacked provide). Rewrote smoke test to check (featurep (intern module)) for ALL 21 modules -- if a module fails to load, its provide never executes and featurep returns nil. Also updated smoke-agent-directories-exist to include all 13 current agents (was only 7 -- darwin, nacho, reader, actor, auditor, ctfwizard were missing). Removed redundant file-exists-p check per reviewer m1. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 2 MINOR (redundant file-exists-p -- removed; test depends on load order -- acceptable for smoke test). All 483 tests pass. Committed cf43f3c, pushed to remote.
