[2026-07-05 09:49:52] darwin: cycle 73 -- fixed user-error double-wrapping in my-gptel-summarize-memories (memory_tools.el). The outer condition-case had only an (error ...) handler. When the body signaled user-error (from curl-error or write-error paths), the (error ...) handler caught it (user-error is a subclass of error) and wrapped the message with 'Memory summarization failed:', producing double-wrapped messages like 'Memory summarization failed: Error: curl exited with code 7'. Fix: added a (user-error ...) handler before the (error ...) handler that re-signals unchanged via (signal (car err) (cdr err)). Also changed the 'conversation too short' check from (error ...) to (user-error ...) per reviewer M1 (pre-existing issue exposed by the new handler structure). Added 3 tests: curl-error passthrough, write-error passthrough, generic error still wrapped. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 3 MINOR (pre-existing error->user-error on conversation-too-short -- fixed; test assertion adequacy -- confirmed correct; comment quality -- good). All 486 tests pass. Committed 671c0a3, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 10:15:11] darwin: cycle 74 -- replaced control char blocklist with allowlist regex in my-gptel--safe-agent-file-p (session_persistence.el). The old approach (built incrementally across cycles 51, 67, 72) blocked specific dangerous characters via character ranges but missed Unicode line separators (U+2028, U+2029, U+0085), spaces, and backslashes. The new allowlist regex \\`[a-zA-Z0-9/._-]+\\' only permits safe path characters, catching all non-allowed characters at once. This is the fundamental fix recommended by the reviewer in cycle 72. Also anchored the prompt.org suffix check to a path separator per reviewer M1: changed string-suffix-p "prompt.org" to (or (string= val "prompt.org") (string-suffix-p "/prompt.org" val)) to prevent false positives like "notprompt.org". Added 6 new tests: Unicode separators (U+2028, U+2029, U+0085) rejection, space and backslash rejection, valid paths with only allowed characters acceptance, bare filename acceptance, suffix anchoring rejection (notprompt.org), and conservative .. rejection (v1..2/prompt.org). Removed redundant concat in Unicode tests per reviewer m2. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 4 MINOR (suffix not anchored -- fixed; redundant concat -- fixed; conservative .. rejection -- documented with test; no test for bare prompt.org -- added), 2 QUESTIONS (agent dir names with non-allowed chars -- confirmed consistent with existing regex; tilde in paths -- confirmed expand-file-name resolves before saving). All 489 tests pass. Committed 9aef91c, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 10:28:07] darwin: cycle 75 -- converted my-gptel--delegate-max-depth and my-gptel--delegate-max-turns from defconst to defcustom in delegate_tool.el. These are user-configurable settings (delegation recursion limit and text-only turn limit) that users may want to customize via M-x customize. All other configurable values in the codebase already use defcustom with :group 'gptel. Added :type 'integer and :group 'gptel to both. Also renamed test test-delegate-max-depth-constant to test-delegate-max-depth-default per reviewer M1 (variable is no longer a constant). Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 1 MAJOR (stale test name -- fixed), 5 MINOR (:type allows zero/negative -- noted; no :safe property -- noted; defconst->defcustom redefinition clean -- confirmed; :group 'gptel correct -- confirmed; continue-prompt stays defconst -- correct), 2 QUESTIONS (test value-agnostic -- confirmed intentional; per-buffer customization -- YAGNI for now). All 489 tests pass. Committed 653553f, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 10:50:04] darwin: cycle 76 -- fixed sentinel buffer-local capture bug in code_tools.el. The sentinel lambda in my-gptel--async-shell-command called my-gptel--maybe-sanitize-exec-output which reads the buffer-local my-gptel--sanitize-exec-output. Process sentinels run in whatever buffer is current when the process exits, NOT the chat buffer that initiated the command. Since the flag is defvar-local, the sentinel would read the wrong buffer's value (likely nil), silently skipping sanitization even when the agent enabled it. Fix: capture the flag at call time in the let* bindings via bound-and-true-p, use the captured value directly in the sentinel closure. Also updated stale comment referencing my-gptel--maybe-sanitize-exec-output (code now calls my-gptel--sanitize-external-output directly). Added 5 tests: 4 functional tests (enabled/disabled/ansi/injection) and 1 regression test using setq-local + buffer switching to verify the flag is captured at call time. Reviewer found the 4 functional tests would pass with the old code too (let binding creates global dynamic binding visible at sentinel time), so added the regression test that uses setq-local + explicit buffer switching to distinguish old from new. All 494 tests pass. Committed 6b36f76, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 11:15:09] darwin: cycle 77 -- extracted duplicated unknown-tool-guard lambda into named function my-gptel--block-unknown-tools in delegate_tool.el. Both delegate_tool.el and darwin_cycle.el had identical inline lambdas registered as gptel-pre-tool-call-functions hooks to block hallucinated tool names. Both call sites now use #'my-gptel--block-unknown-tools. darwin_cycle.el has a declare-function for the new function. Reviewer found CRITICAL: the original docstring incorrectly claimed gptel does NOT handle unknown tools and the FSM hangs in TOOL state forever. In fact, gptel's gptel--handle-tool-use (gptel-request.el line 1968-1972) DOES call process-tool-result for unknown tools, setting :result and allowing the FSM to progress. The hook provides earlier interception at TPRE with a cleaner error message, not a fix for a FSM hang. Rewrote the docstring to accurately describe the hook's purpose. Also documented that the function uses gptel-tools (not info :tools) because the pre-tool-call hook plist does not include a :tools key -- gptel only passes :name, :args, :buffer, :backend, :model. Reviewer also noted the function checks gptel-tools (live variable) vs gptel's own code using (plist-get info :tools) (request snapshot) -- a pre-existing inconsistency not introduced by this refactoring. All 494 tests pass. Committed b50691d, pushed to remote.
