[2026-07-05 12:14:09] darwin: cycle 80 -- fixed empty-string Telegram notification bug in darwin--notify-on-exit (darwin_cycle.el). The old guard (when darwin-cycle-result-message) treats empty strings as truthy in Emacs Lisp, so if the variable was set to "" an empty Telegram message would be sent. Fixed by adding stringp and string-empty-p guards: (when (and (stringp darwin-cycle-result-message) (not (string-empty-p darwin-cycle-result-message))) ...). Also updated defvar docstring to document the non-empty string requirement. Reviewer found 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 3 MINOR (whitespace-only strings not guarded -- unlikely in practice; non-string test only covered integer -- added t case; defvar docstring stale -- fixed). Added 3 tests: empty-string-no-send, non-string-no-send (integer 42), boolean-true-no-send (t -- the canonical accidentally-truthy value). All 499 tests pass. Committed ddf45a2, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 12:22:41] darwin: cycle 81 -- guarded gptel-abort with buffer-live-p in darwin_cycle.el timeout handler. The timeout handler called (gptel-abort cycle-buf) unconditionally, which could crash if the cycle buffer had already been killed (by a prior timer or user action in interactive mode). gptel-abort triggers gptel--fsm-transition to ABRT, which calls gptel--handle-post, which runs :post functions that may access the dead buffer via with-current-buffer. While the callback call inside gptel-abort is wrapped in with-demoted-errors, the FSM transition and :post functions are not. Fix: wrap gptel-abort in (when (buffer-live-p cycle-buf) ...), consistent with the buffer-live-p guard already used 3 lines above for partial response capture and in the continuation hook. Reviewer approved with 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 3 MINOR (orphaned curl process when abort skipped -- mitigated by kill-emacs timer 3s later; two separate buffer-live-p checks in sequence -- benign in single-threaded Emacs; consistency with existing patterns confirmed). Reviewer also noted pre-existing issue: gptel-abort only aborts the main cycle buffer's request, not delegate sub-agent requests. All 499 tests pass. Committed 6b9b67b, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 12:44:22] darwin: cycle 82 -- fixed misleading docstring on my-gptel--guard-check-replace in file_guard.el. The old docstring said "Same restrictions as write -- HISTORY.log is blocked for replace just as it is for write (only append is allowed for HISTORY.log)." This was misleading because it implied independent HISTORY.log blocking logic, when the function is a pure delegation to my-gptel--guard-check-write. The new docstring accurately describes the delegation relationship and explains why HISTORY.log is blocked (it is in my-gptel--guard-always-protected, which guard-check-write checks via my-gptel--guard--active-patterns). Addresses pre-existing reviewer note from cycle 28. No code logic changed, only the docstring. Reviewer approved with 0 CRITICAL, 0 MAJOR, 1 MINOR (minor precision nit about indirection layer -- not blocking). All 499 tests pass. Committed 7b2d63e, pushed to remote.
[2026-07-05 13:09:13] darwin: cycle 83 -- tightened finished.*cycle regex to bounded pattern with word boundary in darwin--cycle-complete-p (darwin_cycle.el). The old pattern 'finished.*cycle' had two false positives: (1) 'finished the review before the cycle started' matched because .* spans arbitrary distance on the same line, and (2) 'finished working on the bicycle' matched because 'cycle' is a substring of 'bicycle'. The new pattern 'finished \\(?:[a-z]+ \\)\\{0,2\\}cycle\\>' allows 0-2 lowercase words between 'finished' and 'cycle' with a word-boundary anchor (\\>) after 'cycle', preventing substring matches like 'cycles' or 'bicycle'. Reviewer found 3 MAJOR issues: (1) 'finished the cycles' still matched because regex had no word-boundary after 'cycle' -- fixed by adding \\> anchor; (2) stale docstring on pre-existing test test-darwin-cycle-complete-finished-current-cycle referencing old 'finished.*cycle' pattern -- fixed; (3) near-duplicate test (old and new both test same input) -- old test kept with updated docstring since it tests a valid case. Also noted MINOR: [a-z]+ matches uppercase with case-fold-search=t (desired behavior), double-space edge case, pre-existing byte-compile warnings. Added 8 new tests: positive matches (the current cycle, my cycle, this cycle, a cycle, our cycle) and negative matches (review before cycle, bicycle, cycles of debugging). Updated stale docstring on pre-existing test. All 507 tests pass. Committed 58a4e0f, pushed to remote.
